{"title_page": "Hotel Milan", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Hotel Milan\n| image = Hotel Milan.jpg\n| alt = \n| director = [[Vishal Mishra (director)|Vishal Mishra]]\n| producer = Haresh Patel\n| writer = {{unbulleted list|Vishal Mishra|Aabhar Dadhich}}\n| starring = {{unbulleted list||[[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]|[[Karishma Sharma]]|[[Zeishan Quadri]]|[[Jaideep Ahlawat]]|[[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]]|[[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]]|Malvi Malhotra}}\n| music = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| editing = Sanjay Sankla\n| studio = AD Films\n| runtime = 130 mins.\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2018|11|16|India}}\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi]]\n}}\n\n'''''Hotel Milan''''' is a 2018 Indian comedy drama film directed by [[Vishal Mishra (Director)|Vishal Mishra]] and features [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]], [[Karishma Sharma]], [[Zeishan Quadri]], [[Jaideep Ahlawat]], [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] and [[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]].\n\nBased on the Anti-Romeo Squads formed by the [[Yogi Adityanath ministry]] in Uttar Pradesh, ''Hotel Milan'' was shot in Kanpur and Unnao. The film was released on 16 November 2018.\n\n==Plot== \nThe film begins with news clips reporting on the Anti-Romeo Squads formed in [[Uttar Pradesh]], with the purpose to prevent [[eve teasing]] and harassment of women at public places, harassing and humiliating young couples. Goldie Kaushik ([[Jaideep Ahlawat]]) is the leader of Bharat Nirmaan Party's Youth Wing in Kanpur and [[moral police|beats up young couples seen together]] in the name of protecting Indian culture. Given his political position, police too helps him in his activities. Vipul ([[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]) is chastised by his father for his joblessness and loitering around the city, while his girlfriend Shaheen ([[Karishma Sharma]]) does not like his opposition to Kaushik; ultimately breaking up with him for this reason. Desperate to win back her affection and earn money, Vipul decides to open a hotel for young couples, along with his friend Saurabh ([[Zeishan Quadri]]). They rent an old lodge belonging to Saurabh's uncle ([[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]]) and make him a partner in their hotel named \"Hotel Milan: Khilte Hain Gul Yahan Khil Ke Bikharne Ko\".\n\nThey charge customers on hourly basis and very soon the hotel becomes a popular destination for young couples to spend time together without the fear of Anti-Romeo Squads and public shaming. The trio is turning in huge profit daily and Shaheen patches up with Vipul. They book a room in the latter's hotel on [[Valentine's Day]] but instead go to a nearby ''dargah'' on Shaheen's insistence. In Vipul's absence, Kaushik reaches the Hotel with his goons. They vandalise the hotel and beat up Saurabh and his uncle. Kaushik's goons drag out the couples from their rooms and thrash them mercilessly. Vipul and Shaheen return to find the hotel ransacked. Together they admit the injured to a nearby hospital and deliberate on their next step. The incident gains huge media coverage and Vipul is invited to one such discussion, where he is disheartened by the repeated haggling of Kaushik and an other politician. Vipul returns home and informs his friends and family that he is going to file a case against Kaushik and ACP Yadav for vandalising his hotel and beating up his customers and staff. They engage the services of Guptaji ([[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]]), a lawyer who has not a won a single case till then and is depressed because his wife ran away with his servant.\n\nDuring the court trial, Kaushik has a case filed against Vipul for [[Prostitution in India|running an immoral place]] and sends goons at Guptaji's residence to intimidate him. The latter manages to get over his wife and presents an incriminating witness in court who had seen Kaushik and his goons beating up young couples outside Milan Hotel and vandalising it. In its judgement, the court comments that the Hotel Milan had been vandalised in a planned conspiracy. It instructs police to suspend ACP Yadav and set up an inquiry against him. To Kaushik, the court awards a fine of {{INRConvert|3.00|l}} and orders him to pay {{INRConvert|20.00|l}} to the owners of Hotel Milan in compensation. In the end of the film Vipul joins Kaushik's party stating that his fight against Kaushik was not a personal one.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]] as Vipul\n* [[Karishma Sharma]] as Shaheen\n* [[Zeishan Quadri]] as Saurabh\n* [[Jaideep Ahlawat]] as Goldie Kaushik\n* [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] as Guptaji\n* [[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]] as Chachaji\n* Malvi Malhotra as Sapna\n\n==Production==\nAfter the formation of [[Yogi Adityanath ministry]] in Uttar Pradesh, Anti-Romeo Squad were set up to prevent [[eve teasing]], ensure safety of women at public places and to \"create fear among potential harassers\". The squads drew criticism when videos of them harassing young couples surfaced in media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ensure 'no unnecessary harassment' by anti-Romeo squad: UP CM|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/602962/ensure-no-unnecessary-harassment-anti.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |date=24 March 2017}}</ref> Vishal Mishra approached Haresh Patel of AD Films with the idea of a film based on \"Anti-Romeo Squads\", who agreed to produce it after the first narration. Mishra described it as \"quite a daring film\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Check out the first look Poster of Bollywood's next controversial film, \u2018Hotel Milan\u2019 |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/check-out-the-first-look-poster-of-bollywoods-next-controversial-film-hotel-milan-4736491.html |publisher=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> He cast [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]], [[Karishma Sharma]], [[Zeishan Quadri]] and [[Jaideep Ahlawat]] for various roles in the film. When questioned by the media regarding the controversial subject of the film, Misha responded that he was not expecting any protest against it.<ref name=\"PTI\">{{cite news |title=I don't expect any protests against film: 'Hotel Milan' director |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/i-dont-expect-any-protests-against-film-hotel-milan-director/1368589 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |agency=[[Press Trust of India]] |date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's principal photography began in [[Kanpur]], Uttar Pradesh on 18 July, 2017. They shot the hotel scenes at an abandoned bungalow after renovating it. Some of the scenes were shot in [[Unnao]]. ''Hotel Milan'' marked the first film of Karishma Sharma in a leading role. She was previously seen in ''[[Pyaar Ka Punchnama 2]]''. She joined the cast later in Kanpur.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jha |first1=Sumit |title=I\u2019m happy that I am back in Kanpur: Kunaal Roy Kapur|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kanpur/im-happy-that-i-am-back-in-kanpur-kunaal-roy-kapur/articleshow/59667650.cms |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=20 July 2017}}</ref> A.B. Vidyalaya Inter College, Mall Road was used for the court scenes. Guptar Ghat, Swaroop Nagar, Moti Jheel and Birhana Road were also used for [[location shooting]]. In total the film crew spent thirty five days in Kanpur and had local actors in supporting roles.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dwivedi |first1=Aishwarya |title=\u092f\u0939\u093e\u0902 \u091a\u0932 \u0930\u0939\u0940 \u2018\u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928\u2019 \u0915\u0940 \u0936\u0942\u091f\u093f\u0902\u0917, \u2018\u0917\u0948\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0938 \u0911\u092b \u0935\u093e\u0938\u0947\u092a\u0941\u0930\u2019 \u0914\u0930 \u2018\u092c\u091c\u0930\u0902\u0917\u0940 \u092d\u093e\u0908\u091c\u093e\u0928\u2019 \u0915\u0947 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u0930 \u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0939\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u092e|url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/kanpur/film-shooting-in-kanpur?pageId=3 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Amar Ujala]] |date=22 July 2017 |location=Kanpur |language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shukla |first1=Gaurav |title=\u092e\u0947\u0930\u0940 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e \u2018\u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928\u2019 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0926\u093f\u0916\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0915\u0948\u0938\u0947-\u0915\u0948\u0938\u0947 \u0917\u0941\u0932 \u0916\u093f\u0932\u093e\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u091b\u094b\u091f\u0947 \u0936\u0939\u0930\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u0935 \u092c\u0930\u094d\u0921\u094d\u0938\u0903 \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e |url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/kanpur/film-director-vishal-mishra-in-kanpur?pageId=4 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Amar Ujala]] |date=10 August 2017 |location=Kanpur |language=Hindi}}</ref> Kapur and Mishra would later come together for ''[[Marudhar Express (film)|Marudhar Express]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Raman |first1=Sruthi Ganapathy |title=\u2018I actually enjoy the supporting roles more\u2019: Why Kunaal Roy Kapur is happy to be \u2018Side Hero\u2019 |url=https://scroll.in/reel/895259/i-actually-enjoy-the-supporting-roles-more-why-kunaal-roy-kapur-is-happy-to-be-side-hero |publisher=[[Scroll.in]] |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film's initial release date was 14 September, 2018 which was later changed to 26 October, 2018.<ref name=\"PTI\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Welcome to Hotel Milan |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/lifestyle/welcome-to-hotel-milan-620521 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=15 July 2018}}</ref> However, the film got further delayed due to late certification from the [[Central Board of Film Certification]] (CBFC). The board instructed the director to remove news footage showing [[Yogi Adityanath]] which had been used in the film's trailer. Mishra removed the video but kept Adityanath's audio in the film.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Varma |first1=Lipika |title=Censor axe on Hotel Milan |url=https://www.asianage.com/entertainment/bollywood/131118/censor-axe-on-hotel-milan.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Asian Age]] |date=13 November 2018}}</ref> The film was eventually released on 16 November, 2018, a week following [[Diwali]].<ref name=\"TOI\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jha |first1=Lata |title=Friday film wrap: Post-Diwali week sees a bunch of small releases |url=https://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/fQWWB0PN2U6j2j1LpTOrHO/Friday-film-wrap-PostDiwali-week-sees-a-bunch-of-small-rel.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]] |date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hotel Milan\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Harshit Saxena]], Kashi-Richard, Amjad Nadeem, Enbee & Ruchit H Patel\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 August 2018<ref name=\"Saavn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.saavn.com/s/album/hindi/Hotel-Milan-2018/TWmT6TSpFfw_|title=Hotel Milan - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=[[Saavn]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 2018\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 23:41\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[Zee Music Company]]\n| producer   = \n| misc = {{External media\n| audio2 = {{YouTube|ZQMx5CJ-0OM|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's soundtrack album is composed by [[Harshit Saxena]], Kashi-Richard, Amjad Nadeem, Enbee & Ruchit H Patel.<ref name=\"Saavn\" />\n\n{{Track listing\n\n| headline = Track listing<ref name=\"Saavn\" />\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 23:41\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = \n| title1 = Stepney\n| lyrics1 = [[Kumaar]]\n| music1 = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| extra1 = Harshit Saxena\n| length1 = 3:39\n| title2 = Saansein\n| lyrics2 = Sanjeev Chaturvedi\n| music2 = Ruchit H Patel, Kashi-Richard\n| extra2 = Ruchit H Patel\n| length2 = 4:38\n| title3 = Hotel Milan Title Track\n| lyrics3 = Amjad Nadeem\n| music3 = Amjad Nadeem\n| extra3 = [[Brijesh Shandilya]], Shyamoli Sanghi\n| length3 = 3:26\n| title4 = Badi Happening Lagti Ho\n| lyrics4 = Enbee\n| music4 = Enbee\n| extra4 = [[Jyotica Tangri]], Enbee & Raahi\n| length4 = 2:45\n| title5 = Allaudin\n| lyrics5 = Dev Narayan\n| music5 = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| extra5 = Harshit Saxena Feat. [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] & Shailey Bidwaikar\n| length5 = 2:55\n| title6 = Aa Zara\n| lyrics6 = Amjad Nadeem\n| music6 = Amjad Nadeem\n| extra6 = Aakanksha Sharma\n| length6 = 3:33\n| title7 = Allaudin - Version\n| lyrics7 = Dev Narayan\n| music7 = Harshit Saxena\n| extra7 = Harshit Saxena & Shailey Bidwaikar\n| length7 = 2:55\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nPallabi Dey Purkayastha of ''[[The Times of India]]'' gave the film 1.5 star rating out of a maximum five. She called Quadri's character the \"only saving grace\" of the film, which to her was \"as shady as a love hotel\". She stated that Kapur was a \"misfit\" who struggled with the Kanpur accent and Sharma as \"outrageously overdressed\". Purkayastha felt that the plot's novelty was the only thing \"[working] in favour of the director\".<ref name=\"TOI\">{{cite news |last1=Purkayastha |first1=Pallabi Dey |title=Hotel Milan Movie Review |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hotel-milan/movie-review/66684687.cms |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=17 November 2018}} {{Rating|1.5|5}}</ref>\n\nWriting for the ''[[Mumbai Mirror]]'', Kunal Guha was critical of the film and gave it a 1-star rating, calling it a film with low \"production values\" and a \"kind of project you\u2019d not wish on your worst enemy\". He felt that the film was poor on technical front and that some of the staff might have \"walked off the project midway\" adding pressure on the staff that remained. He likened the film to \"mediocre sitcoms\" for its \"jarring laughter track\". On the film's character, Guha noted that Quadri was \"barely tolerable\" and Kapur's acting was \"[discomforting]\". He advised Ahlawat to be careful while going through a film's script.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guha |first1=Kunal |title=Hotel Milan review: Kunaal Roy Kapur's film is not worth a watch |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-review/hotel-milan-review-kunaal-roy-kapurs-film-is-not-worth-a-watch/articleshow/66654819.cms |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=16 November 2018}} {{Rating|1|5}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kanpur]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kanpur]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Hotel Milan\n| image = Hotel Milan.jpg\n| alt = \n| director = [[Vishal Mishra (director)|Vishal Mishra]]\n| producer = Haresh Patel\n| writer = {{unbulleted list|Vishal Mishra|Aabhar Dadhich}}\n| starring = {{unbulleted list||[[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]|[[Karishma Sharma]]|[[Zeishan Quadri]]|[[Jaideep Ahlawat]]|[[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]]|[[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]]|Malvi Malhotra}}\n| music = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| editing = Sanjay Sankla\n| studio = AD Films\n| runtime = 130 mins.\n| released = {{Film date|df=yes|2018|11|16|India}}\n| country = [[India]]\n| language = [[Hindi]]\n}}\n\n'''''Hotel Milan''''' is a 2018 Indian comedy drama film directed by [[Vishal Mishra (Director)|Vishal Mishra]] and features [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]], [[Karishma Sharma]], [[Zeishan Quadri]], [[Jaideep Ahlawat]], [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] and [[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]].\n\nBased on the Anti-Romeo Squads formed by the [[Yogi Adityanath ministry]] in Uttar Pradesh, ''Hotel Milan'' was shot in Kanpur and Unnao. The film was released on 16 November 2018.\n\n==Plot== \nThe film begins with news clips reporting on the Anti-Romeo Squads formed in [[Uttar Pradesh]], with the purpose to prevent [[eve teasing]] and harassment of women at public places, harassing and humiliating young couples. Goldie Kaushik ([[Jaideep Ahlawat]]) is the leader of Bharat Nirmaan Party's Youth Wing in Kanpur and [[moral police|beats up young couples seen together]] in the name of protecting Indian culture. Given his political position, police too helps him in his activities. Vipul ([[Kunaal Roy Kapur]]) is chastised by his father for his joblessness and loitering around the city, while his girlfriend Shaheen ([[Karishma Sharma]]) does not like his opposition to Kaushik; ultimately breaking up with him for this reason. Desperate to win back her affection and earn money, Vipul decides to open a hotel for young couples, along with his friend Saurabh ([[Zeishan Quadri]]). They rent an old lodge belonging to Saurabh's uncle ([[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]]) and make him a partner in their hotel named \"Hotel Milan: Khilte Hain Gul Yahan Khil Ke Bikharne Ko\".\n\nThey charge customers on hourly basis and very soon the hotel becomes a popular destination for young couples to spend time together without the fear of Anti-Romeo Squads and public shaming. The trio is turning in huge profit daily and Shaheen patches up with Vipul. They book a room in the latter's hotel on [[Valentine's Day]] but instead go to a nearby ''dargah'' on Shaheen's insistence. In Vipul's absence, Kaushik reaches the Hotel with his goons. They vandalise the hotel and beat up Saurabh and his uncle. Kaushik's goons drag out the couples from their rooms and thrash them mercilessly. Vipul and Shaheen return to find the hotel ransacked. Together they admit the injured to a nearby hospital and deliberate on their next step. The incident gains huge media coverage and Vipul is invited to one such discussion, where he is disheartened by the repeated haggling of Kaushik and an other politician. Vipul returns home and informs his friends and family that he is going to file a case against Kaushik and ACP Yadav for vandalising his hotel and beating up his customers and staff. They engage the services of Guptaji ([[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]]), a lawyer who has not a won a single case till then and is depressed because his wife ran away with his servant.\n\nDuring the court trial, Kaushik has a case filed against Vipul for [[Prostitution in India|running an immoral place]] and sends goons at Guptaji's residence to intimidate him. The latter manages to get over his wife and presents an incriminating witness in court who had seen Kaushik and his goons beating up young couples outside Milan Hotel and vandalising it. In its judgement, the court comments that the Hotel Milan had been vandalised in a planned conspiracy. It instructs police to suspend ACP Yadav and set up an inquiry against him. To Kaushik, the court awards a fine of {{INRConvert|3.00|l}} and orders him to pay {{INRConvert|20.00|l}} to the owners of Hotel Milan in compensation. In the end of the film Vipul joins Kaushik's party stating that his fight against Kaushik was not a personal one.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]] as Vipul\n* [[Karishma Sharma]] as Shaheen\n* [[Zeishan Quadri]] as Saurabh\n* [[Jaideep Ahlawat]] as Goldie Kaushik\n* [[Rajesh Sharma (actor)|Rajesh Sharma]] as Guptaji\n* [[Zakir Hussain (actor)|Zakir Hussain]] as Chachaji\n* Malvi Malhotra as Sapna\n\n==Production==\nAfter the formation of [[Yogi Adityanath ministry]] in Uttar Pradesh, Anti-Romeo Squad were set up to prevent [[eve teasing]], ensure safety of women at public places and to \"create fear among potential harassers\". The squads drew criticism when videos of them harassing young couples surfaced in media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Ensure 'no unnecessary harassment' by anti-Romeo squad: UP CM|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/content/602962/ensure-no-unnecessary-harassment-anti.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Deccan Herald]] |date=24 March 2017}}</ref> Vishal Mishra approached Haresh Patel of AD Films with the idea of a film based on \"Anti-Romeo Squads\", who agreed to produce it after the first narration. Mishra described it as \"quite a daring film\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Check out the first look Poster of Bollywood's next controversial film, \u2018Hotel Milan\u2019 |url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/check-out-the-first-look-poster-of-bollywoods-next-controversial-film-hotel-milan-4736491.html |publisher=[[Firstpost]] |accessdate=13 April 2020 |date=13 July 2018}}</ref> He cast [[Kunaal Roy Kapur]], [[Karishma Sharma]], [[Zeishan Quadri]] and [[Jaideep Ahlawat]] for various roles in the film. When questioned by the media regarding the controversial subject of the film, Misha responded that he was not expecting any protest against it.<ref name=\"PTI\">{{cite news |title=I don't expect any protests against film: 'Hotel Milan' director |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/i-dont-expect-any-protests-against-film-hotel-milan-director/1368589 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[Outlook (Indian magazine)|Outlook]] |agency=[[Press Trust of India]] |date=21 August 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe film's principal photography began in [[Kanpur]], Uttar Pradesh on 18 July, 2017. They shot the hotel scenes at an abandoned bungalow after renovating it. Some of the scenes were shot in [[Unnao]]. ''Hotel Milan'' marked the first film of Karishma Sharma in a leading role. She was previously seen in ''[[Pyaar Ka Punchnama 2]]''. She joined the cast later in Kanpur.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jha |first1=Sumit |title=I\u2019m happy that I am back in Kanpur: Kunaal Roy Kapur|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kanpur/im-happy-that-i-am-back-in-kanpur-kunaal-roy-kapur/articleshow/59667650.cms |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=20 July 2017}}</ref> A.B. Vidyalaya Inter College, Mall Road was used for the court scenes. Guptar Ghat, Swaroop Nagar, Moti Jheel and Birhana Road were also used for [[location shooting]]. In total the film crew spent thirty five days in Kanpur and had local actors in supporting roles.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dwivedi |first1=Aishwarya |title=\u092f\u0939\u093e\u0902 \u091a\u0932 \u0930\u0939\u0940 \u2018\u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928\u2019 \u0915\u0940 \u0936\u0942\u091f\u093f\u0902\u0917, \u2018\u0917\u0948\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0938 \u0911\u092b \u0935\u093e\u0938\u0947\u092a\u0941\u0930\u2019 \u0914\u0930 \u2018\u092c\u091c\u0930\u0902\u0917\u0940 \u092d\u093e\u0908\u091c\u093e\u0928\u2019 \u0915\u0947 \u090f\u0915\u094d\u091f\u0930 \u0915\u0930 \u0930\u0939\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u092e|url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/kanpur/film-shooting-in-kanpur?pageId=3 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Amar Ujala]] |date=22 July 2017 |location=Kanpur |language=Hindi}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Shukla |first1=Gaurav |title=\u092e\u0947\u0930\u0940 \u092b\u093f\u0932\u094d\u092e \u2018\u0939\u094b\u091f\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0932\u0928\u2019 \u092e\u0947\u0902 \u0926\u093f\u0916\u0947\u0917\u093e \u0915\u0948\u0938\u0947-\u0915\u0948\u0938\u0947 \u0917\u0941\u0932 \u0916\u093f\u0932\u093e\u0924\u0947 \u0939\u0948\u0902 \u091b\u094b\u091f\u0947 \u0936\u0939\u0930\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u0935 \u092c\u0930\u094d\u0921\u094d\u0938\u0903 \u0935\u093f\u0936\u093e\u0932 \u092e\u093f\u0936\u094d\u0930\u093e |url=https://www.amarujala.com/uttar-pradesh/kanpur/film-director-vishal-mishra-in-kanpur?pageId=4 |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Amar Ujala]] |date=10 August 2017 |location=Kanpur |language=Hindi}}</ref> Kapur and Mishra would later come together for ''[[Marudhar Express (film)|Marudhar Express]]'' (2019).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Raman |first1=Sruthi Ganapathy |title=\u2018I actually enjoy the supporting roles more\u2019: Why Kunaal Roy Kapur is happy to be \u2018Side Hero\u2019 |url=https://scroll.in/reel/895259/i-actually-enjoy-the-supporting-roles-more-why-kunaal-roy-kapur-is-happy-to-be-side-hero |publisher=[[Scroll.in]] |accessdate=14 April 2020 |date=25 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\nThe film's initial release date was 14 September, 2018 which was later changed to 26 October, 2018.<ref name=\"PTI\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=Welcome to Hotel Milan |url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/archive/lifestyle/welcome-to-hotel-milan-620521 |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Tribune (Chandigarh)|The Tribune]] |date=15 July 2018}}</ref> However, the film got further delayed due to late certification from the [[Central Board of Film Certification]] (CBFC). The board insructed the director to remove news footage showing [[Yogi Adityanath]] which had been used in the film's trailer. Mishra removed the video but kept Adityanath's audio in the film.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Varma |first1=Lipika |title=Censor axe on Hotel Milan |url=https://www.asianage.com/entertainment/bollywood/131118/censor-axe-on-hotel-milan.html |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Asian Age]] |date=13 November 2018}}</ref> The film was eventually released on 16 November, 2018, a week following [[Diwali]].<ref name=\"TOI\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jha |first1=Lata |title=Friday film wrap: Post-Diwali week sees a bunch of small releases |url=https://www.livemint.com/Home-Page/fQWWB0PN2U6j2j1LpTOrHO/Friday-film-wrap-PostDiwali-week-sees-a-bunch-of-small-rel.html |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Mint (newspaper)|Mint]] |date=16 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Soundtrack==\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Hotel Milan\n| type       = soundtrack\n| artist     = [[Harshit Saxena]], Kashi-Richard, Amjad Nadeem, Enbee & Ruchit H Patel\n| cover      =\n| alt        =\n| released   = 28 August 2018<ref name=\"Saavn\">{{cite web|url=https://www.saavn.com/s/album/hindi/Hotel-Milan-2018/TWmT6TSpFfw_|title=Hotel Milan - Original Motion Picture Soundtrack |publisher=[[Saavn]] |accessdate=14 April 2020}}</ref>\n| recorded   = 2018\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Feature film soundtrack]]\n| length     = 23:41\n| language   = [[Hindi]]\n| label      = [[Zee Music Company]]\n| producer   = \n| misc = {{External media\n| audio2 = {{YouTube|ZQMx5CJ-0OM|Official Audio Jukebox}}\n}}}}\n\nThe film's soundtrack album is composed by [[Harshit Saxena]], Kashi-Richard, Amjad Nadeem, Enbee & Ruchit H Patel.<ref name=\"Saavn\" />\n\n{{Track listing\n\n| headline = Track listing<ref name=\"Saavn\" />\n| extra_column = Singer(s)\n| total_length = 23:41\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = \n| title1 = Stepney\n| lyrics1 = [[Kumaar]]\n| music1 = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| extra1 = Harshit Saxena\n| length1 = 3:39\n| title2 = Saansein\n| lyrics2 = Sanjeev Chaturvedi\n| music2 = Ruchit H Patel, Kashi-Richard\n| extra2 = Ruchit H Patel\n| length2 = 4:38\n| title3 = Hotel Milan Title Track\n| lyrics3 = Amjad Nadeem\n| music3 = Amjad Nadeem\n| extra3 = [[Brijesh Shandilya]], Shyamoli Sanghi\n| length3 = 3:26\n| title4 = Badi Happening Lagti Ho\n| lyrics4 = Enbee\n| music4 = Enbee\n| extra4 = [[Jyotica Tangri]], Enbee & Raahi\n| length4 = 2:45\n| title5 = Allaudin\n| lyrics5 = Dev Narayan\n| music5 = [[Harshit Saxena]]\n| extra5 = Harshit Saxena Feat. [[Shaan (singer)|Shaan]] & Shailey Bidwaikar\n| length5 = 2:55\n| title6 = Aa Zara\n| lyrics6 = Amjad Nadeem\n| music6 = Amjad Nadeem\n| extra6 = Aakanksha Sharma\n| length6 = 3:33\n| title7 = Allaudin - Version\n| lyrics7 = Dev Narayan\n| music7 = Harshit Saxena\n| extra7 = Harshit Saxena & Shailey Bidwaikar\n| length7 = 2:55\n}}\n\n==Reception==\nPallabi Dey Purkayastha of ''[[The Times of India]]'' gave the film 1.5 star rating out of a maximum five. She called Quadri's character the \"only saving grace\" of the film, which to her was \"as shady as a love hotel\". She stated that Kapur was a \"misfit\" who struggled with the Kanpur accent and Sharma as \"outrageously overdressed\". Purkayastha felt that the plot's novelty was the only thing \"[working] in favour of the director\".<ref name=\"TOI\">{{cite news |last1=Purkayastha |first1=Pallabi Dey |title=Hotel Milan Movie Review |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/hotel-milan/movie-review/66684687.cms |accessdate=13 April 2020 |work=[[The Times of India]] |date=17 November 2018}} {{Rating|1.5|5}}</ref>\n\nWriting for the ''[[Mumbai Mirror]]'', Kunal Guha was critical of the film and gave it a 1-star rating, calling it a film with low \"production values\" and a \"kind of project you\u2019d not wish on your worst enemy\". He felt that the film was poor on technical front and that some of the staff might have \"walked off the project midway\" adding pressure on the staff that remained. He likened the film to \"mediocre sitcoms\" for its \"jarring laughter track\". On the film's character, Guha noted that Quadri was \"barely tolerable\" and Kapur's acting was \"[discomforting]\". He advised Ahlawat to be careful while going through a film's script.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Guha |first1=Kunal |title=Hotel Milan review: Kunaal Roy Kapur's film is not worth a watch |url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/entertainment/movie-review/hotel-milan-review-kunaal-roy-kapurs-film-is-not-worth-a-watch/articleshow/66654819.cms |accessdate=14 April 2020 |work=[[Mumbai Mirror]] |date=16 November 2018}} {{Rating|1|5}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:Indian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring an item number]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Films set in Kanpur]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Kanpur]]\n", "name_user": "Skr15081997", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hotel_Milan"}
{"title_page": "Good Times (newspaper)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Good Times\n| logo = Good Times logo.png\n| image =\n| caption =\n| type = [[Alternative newspaper|Alternative weekly]]\n| format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| owners = [[Metro Newspapers]]\n| president = [[Dan Pulcrano]]\n| publisher = Dan Pulcrano\n| chiefeditor = Steve Palopoli\n| assoceditor =\n| maneditor =\n| newseditor =\n| managingeditordesign =\n| campuschief =\n| founder = Jay Shore\n| opeditor =\n| sportseditor =\n| photoeditor =\n| seniorstaff =\n| staff =\n| foundation = April 3, 1975<ref name=\"adkit\">[http://www.gtweekly.com/images/MediaKitDownloads/display_rates_gtw.pdf Display & Classified Advertising Media Kit]. Retrieved December 22, 2013.</ref>\n| political =\n| language =\n| ceased publication =\n| relaunched =\n| headquarters = [[Santa Cruz, California]]\n| circulation = 35,000<ref name=\"adkit\" />\n| sister newspapers =\n| ISSN = 0164-4033\n| oclc = 4708924\n| website = {{URL|GoodTimes.sc}}\n}}\n\n'''''Good Times''''' is a free-circulation weekly newspaper based in [[Santa Cruz, California]].  ''Good Times'' is distributed in [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz County]], a coastal area that includes [[Capitola, California|Capitola]], [[Rio del Mar]], [[Aptos]] and [[Watsonville]]. It is owned by the Northern California-based [[Metro Newspapers]].  [[Dan Pulcrano]] is the CEO and executive editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altweeklies.com/aan/metro-newspapers-acquires-good-times-santa-cruz/Article?oid=7611859 | last=Zaragoza | first=Jason | publisher=Association of Alternative Newsmedia| website=altweeklies.com |title=Metro Newspapers Acquires ''Good Times'' Santa Cruz | date= April 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Good Times'' was founded in 1975 by Jay Shore, who remained its owner/operator and editor for 13 years. Shore established ''Good Times'' amidst a proliferation in the 1970s of short-lived free counterculture newspapers in [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz County]] that included ''The Free Spaghetti Dinner'', ''Sundaz!'', ''Santa Cruz Times'', ''People\u2019s Press'' and the ''Santa Cruz Independent''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtweekly.com/index.php/santa-cruz-news/good-times-cover-stories/6494-searching-for-alternatives.html | last=Gant | first=Michael | publisher=Good Times| website=gtweekly.com |title=Searching for Alternatives | date= April 21, 2015 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Shore sold the paper to [[Independent Newspapers]] of New Zealand, part of [[Rupert Murdoch]]\u2019s group of holdings, a year before much of downtown Santa Cruz was destroyed in the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/07.16.98/murdoch-9828.html | last=Yewell | first=John | publisher=Metro Santa Cruz| website=metroactive.com |title=Murdoch Era Ends at Good Times  | date= July 16, 1998 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Independent Newspapers sold ''Good Times'' to Central Valley Publishing, later renamed Pacific-Sierra Publishing.<ref>[http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/07.16.98/murdoch-9828.html  Murdoch Era Ends at Good Times]</ref> In 2003, Pacific-Sierra head Anthony Allegretti lead a buyout to form a new company, MainStreet Media Group.<ref>[http://www.dirksvanessen.com/articles/view/150/management-buyout-leads-to-new-company/ Management Buyout Leads to New Company]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, New England-based Brookside Capital sold ''Good Times.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pehub.com/2014/04/brookside-group-backed-mainstreet-media-sells-four-weeklies// |title=Brookside Group-backed MainStreet Media sells four weeklies |accessdate=April 20, 2014 }}</ref> to [[Metro Newspapers]], which owned the competing ''[[Santa Cruz Weekly]]'', returning the publication to local ownership for the first time since the 1980s. The ''Santa Cruz Weekly'', which began as ''[[Metro Santa Cruz]]'' in 1994, combined operations with ''Good Times'' following the purchase.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2014/03/31/metro-newspapers-buys-weeklies-in-santa-cruz.html Metro Newspapers buys weeklies in Santa Cruz, Gilroy, Morgan Hill and Hollister]</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the sale, former ''Good Times'' publisher Ron Slack complained about the lack of investment in the product by its former owners, saying ''Good Times'' didn't get much support from its corporate parent in upgrades in equipment and software.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/general-news/20140331/good-times-purchased-by-santa-cruz-weekly |publisher=Santa Cruz Sentinel | title=Good Times purchased by Santa Cruz Weekly | author=Wallace Baine | date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n''Good Times'' was an active sponsor with Tom Schot in presenting disc sports to Californians by way of the 1978 [[World Disc Games|Santa Cruz Flying Disc Classic]] and the [[Ken Westerfield#Ultimate Frisbee in Canada (disc ultimate)|Santa Cruz Good Times Ultimate Team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Schot|url=http://www.discgolfhalloffame.org/tom-schot/|work=Disc Golf Hall of Fame|accessdate=February 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027153535/http://www.discgolfhalloffame.org/tom-schot/|archive-date=October 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Good Times'' was the first publication to give voice to [[Rob Brezsny|Rob Brezsny's]] \"Free Will Astrology\" Column.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freewillastrology.com/beauty/beauty.main212.shtml|title=Free Will Astrology : Beauty & Truth Lab|website=freewillastrology.com|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019, Good Times expanded its South County reach with the purchase of the Pulitzer Prize-winning Watsonville Register-Pajaronian, returning it to local control after 78 years of ownership by two multiple-state national media companies. It also acquired as part of the transaction the Aptos Life monthly.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Good Times purchases Watsonville Register-Pajaronian|url=https://www.register-pajaronian.com/article/good-times-purchases-watsonville-register-pajaronian|work=Watsonville Register-Pajaronian |location=Watsonville, California |date=July 1, 2019 | accessdate=July 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Editorial Focus==\n''Good Times'' publishes features  on news, opinion, entertainment, arts and events.<ref>{{cite web |title= Publications |work= web site |publisher= Main Street Media Group, LLC |year= 2008 |url= http://www.mainstreetmg.com/publications.html |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the publication started as a reaction to the political journalism of the 1970s and focused on entertainment. \"Good Times\u2019 motto was 'lighter than air.' They only printed good news,\" recalls former columnist Bruce Bratton.<ref>{{cite web |title= A Santa Cruz Institution |publisher= Coast News |url= http://www.coastnews.com/santa_cruz/bratton/bratton.htm |accessdate= December 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOver time, the weekly has expanded its coverage and since 2000 has won more than 24 awards in editorial competitions. ''Good Times'' won an award for General Excellence in the [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] Better Newspaper Contest 2006\u20132007.<ref>{{cite news |title= Weekly General Excellence Winners |newspaper= The BNC Tab |publisher= [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] |date= July 14, 2007 |volume= 61 |number= 7 |url= http://www.cnpa.com/files/misc/2006%20BNC%20Winner%20Tab.pdf |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref> In 2008 it won first place for environmental and agricultural reporting.<ref>{{cite news |title= 2008 Weekly Winners  By Category |newspaper= The BNC Tab |publisher= [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] |date= October 25, 2008 |url= http://www.cnpa.com//files//2008Webview.pdf |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref> \n\nIn 2018, it placed third in the state among California's largest weeklies for General Excellence.<ref>{{cite news | title= 2018 California Journalism Awards - Print Division | publisher=[[California News Publishers Association]] | url=http://cnpa.com/cja2018/print/gallery/General_Excellence_01_General_Excellence_(WA).html|accessdate= July 2, 2019 }}</ref> In 2019 Good Times won the General Excellence First Place award again, with judges praising the publication for its \u201cexcellent presentation, writing, story choices and quality of the photography\u201d and noting, \u201cThe advertising was attractive and engaging.\u201d<ref>{{cite news | title= 2019 California Journalism Awards Print Contest winners | publisher=[[California News Publishers Association]] | https://cnpa.com/cja/2019print/ |accessdate= April 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |title= ''Good Times'' Santa Cruz |work= online edition and community web portal |url= http://www.gtweekly.com/ |accessdate= 2010-04-01 }}\n\n{{Metro Newspapers}}\n\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1975]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name = Good Times\n| logo = Good Times logo.png\n| image =\n| caption =\n| type = [[Alternative newspaper|Alternative weekly]]\n| format = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| owners = [[Metro Newspapers]]\n| president = [[Dan Pulcrano]]\n| publisher = Dan Pulcrano\n| chiefeditor = Steve Palopoli\n| assoceditor =\n| maneditor =\n| newseditor =\n| managingeditordesign =\n| campuschief =\n| founder = Jay Shore\n| opeditor =\n| sportseditor =\n| photoeditor =\n| seniorstaff =\n| staff =\n| foundation = April 3, 1975<ref name=\"adkit\">[http://www.gtweekly.com/images/MediaKitDownloads/display_rates_gtw.pdf Display & Classified Advertising Media Kit]. Retrieved December 22, 2013.</ref>\n| political =\n| language =\n| ceased publication =\n| relaunched =\n| headquarters = [[Santa Cruz, California]]\n| circulation = 35,000<ref name=\"adkit\" />\n| sister newspapers =\n| ISSN = 0164-4033\n| oclc = 4708924\n| website = {{URL|GoodTimes.sc}}\n}}\n\n'''''Good Times''''' is a free-circulation weekly newspaper based in [[Santa Cruz, California]].  ''Good Times'' is distributed in [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz County]], a coastal area that includes [[Capitola, California|Capitola]], [[Rio del Mar]], [[Aptos]] and [[Watsonville]]. It is owned by the Northern California-based [[Metro Newspapers]].  [[Dan Pulcrano]] is the CEO and executive editor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.altweeklies.com/aan/metro-newspapers-acquires-good-times-santa-cruz/Article?oid=7611859 | last=Zaragoza | first=Jason | publisher=Association of Alternative Newsmedia| website=altweeklies.com |title=Metro Newspapers Acquires ''Good Times'' Santa Cruz | date= April 1, 2014 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Good Times'' was founded in 1975 by Jay Shore, who remained its owner/operator and editor for 13 years. Shore established ''Good Times'' amidst a proliferation in the 1970s of short-lived free counterculture newspapers in [[Santa Cruz County, California|Santa Cruz County]] that included ''The Free Spaghetti Dinner'', ''Sundaz!'', ''Santa Cruz Times'', ''People\u2019s Press'' and the ''Santa Cruz Independent''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gtweekly.com/index.php/santa-cruz-news/good-times-cover-stories/6494-searching-for-alternatives.html | last=Gant | first=Michael | publisher=Good Times| website=gtweekly.com |title=Searching for Alternatives | date= April 21, 2015 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Shore sold the paper to [[Independent Newspapers]] of New Zealand, part of [[Rupert Murdoch]]\u2019s group of holdings, a year before much of downtown Santa Cruz was destroyed in the [[Loma Prieta earthquake]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/07.16.98/murdoch-9828.html | last=Yewell | first=John | publisher=Metro Santa Cruz| website=metroactive.com |title=Murdoch Era Ends at Good Times  | date= July 16, 1998 |accessdate=May 30, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Independent Newspapers sold ''Good Times'' to Central Valley Publishing, later renamed Pacific-Sierra Publishing.<ref>[http://www.metroactive.com/papers/cruz/07.16.98/murdoch-9828.html  Murdoch Era Ends at Good Times]</ref> In 2003, Pacific-Sierra head Anthony Allegretti lead a buyout to form a new company, MainStreet Media Group.<ref>[http://www.dirksvanessen.com/articles/view/150/management-buyout-leads-to-new-company/ Management Buyout Leads to New Company]</ref>\n\nIn 2014, New England-based Brookside Capital sold ''Good Times.''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pehub.com/2014/04/brookside-group-backed-mainstreet-media-sells-four-weeklies// |title=Brookside Group-backed MainStreet Media sells four weeklies |accessdate=April 20, 2014 }}</ref> to [[Metro Newspapers]], which owned the competing ''[[Santa Cruz Weekly]]'', returning the publication to local ownership for the first time since the 1980s. The ''Santa Cruz Weekly'', which began as ''[[Metro Santa Cruz]]'' in 1994, combined operations with ''Good Times'' following the purchase.<ref>[http://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2014/03/31/metro-newspapers-buys-weeklies-in-santa-cruz.html Metro Newspapers buys weeklies in Santa Cruz, Gilroy, Morgan Hill and Hollister]</ref>\n\nOn the eve of the sale, former ''Good Times'' publisher Ron Slack complained about the lack of investment in the product by its former owners, saying ''Good Times'' didn't get much support from its corporate parent in upgrades in equipment and software.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/general-news/20140331/good-times-purchased-by-santa-cruz-weekly |publisher=Santa Cruz Sentinel | title=Good Times purchased by Santa Cruz Weekly | author=Wallace Baine | date=March 31, 2014 |accessdate=December 17, 2014 }}</ref>\n\n''Good Times'' was an active sponsor with Tom Schot in presenting disc sports to Californians by way of the 1978 [[World Disc Games|Santa Cruz Flying Disc Classic]] and the [[Ken Westerfield#Ultimate Frisbee in Canada (disc ultimate)|Santa Cruz Good Times Ultimate Team]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Tom Schot|url=http://www.discgolfhalloffame.org/tom-schot/|work=Disc Golf Hall of Fame|accessdate=February 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141027153535/http://www.discgolfhalloffame.org/tom-schot/|archive-date=October 27, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n''Good Times'' was the first publication to give voice to [[Rob Brezsny|Rob Brezsny's]] \"Free Will Astrology\" Column.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freewillastrology.com/beauty/beauty.main212.shtml|title=Free Will Astrology : Beauty & Truth Lab|website=freewillastrology.com|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019, Good Times expanded its South County reach with the purchase of the Pulitzer Prize-winning Watsonville Register-Pajaronian, returning it to local control after 78 years of ownership by two multiple-state national media companies. It also acquired as part of the transaction the Aptos Life monthly.<ref>{{cite news|author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title= Good Times purchases Watsonville Register-Pajaronian|url=https://www.register-pajaronian.com/article/good-times-purchases-watsonville-register-pajaronian|work=Watsonville Register-Pajaronian |location=Watsonville, California |date=July 1, 2019 | accessdate=July 2, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Editorial Focus==\n''Good Times'' publishes features  on news, opinion, entertainment, arts and events.<ref>{{cite web |title= Publications |work= web site |publisher= Main Street Media Group, LLC |year= 2008 |url= http://www.mainstreetmg.com/publications.html |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nOriginally, the publication started as a reaction to the political journalism of the 1970s and focused on entertainment. \"Good Times\u2019 motto was 'lighter than air.' They only printed good news,\" recalls former columnist Bruce Bratton.<ref>{{cite web |title= A Santa Cruz Institution |publisher= Coast News |url= http://www.coastnews.com/santa_cruz/bratton/bratton.htm |accessdate= December 14, 2014 }}</ref>\n\nOver time, the weekly has expanded its coverage and since 2000 has won more than 24 awards in editorial competitions. ''Good Times'' won an award for General Excellence in the [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] Better Newspaper Contest 2006\u20132007.<ref>{{cite news |title= Weekly General Excellence Winners |newspaper= The BNC Tab |publisher= [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] |date= July 14, 2007 |volume= 61 |number= 7 |url= http://www.cnpa.com/files/misc/2006%20BNC%20Winner%20Tab.pdf |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref> In 2008 it won first place for environmental and agricultural reporting.<ref>{{cite news |title= 2008 Weekly Winners  By Category |newspaper= The BNC Tab |publisher= [[California Newspaper Publishers Association]] |date= October 25, 2008 |url= http://www.cnpa.com//files//2008Webview.pdf |accessdate= April 1, 2010 }}</ref> In 2018, it placed third in the state among California's largest weeklies for General Excellence.<ref>{{cite news | title= 2018 California Journalism Awards - Print Division | publisher=[[California News Publishers Association]] | url=http://cnpa.com/cja2018/print/gallery/General_Excellence_01_General_Excellence_(WA).html|accessdate= July 2, 2019 }}</ref> In 2019 Good Times won the General Excellence First Place award again, with judges praising the publication for its \u201cexcellent presentation, writing, story choices and quality of the photography\u201d and noting, \u201cThe advertising was attractive and engaging.\u201d<ref>{{cite news | title= 2019 California Journalism Awards Print Contest winners | publisher=[[California News Publishers Association]] | https://cnpa.com/cja/2019print/ |accessdate= April 14, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{cite web |title= ''Good Times'' Santa Cruz |work= online edition and community web portal |url= http://www.gtweekly.com/ |accessdate= 2010-04-01 }}\n\n{{Metro Newspapers}}\n\n[[Category:Newspapers published in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1975]]\n[[Category:1975 establishments in California]]\n", "name_user": "Metronews", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEditorial Focus:added paragraph break", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Good_Times_(newspaper)"}
{"title_page": "Pelagius", "text_new": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Undue weight|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Pelagius from Nuremberg Chronicle.jpg|thumb|Illustration of Pelagius in the [[Nuremberg Chronicle]]]]\n\n'''Pelagius'''  ({{circa|AD&nbsp;354}}&nbsp;\u2013 418) was a [[theologian]] who advocated [[free will]] and [[asceticism]]. He was accused by [[Augustine of Hippo]] and others of denying the need for divine aid in performing [[good works]]. They understood him to have said that the only grace necessary was the declaration of the law; humans were not wounded by Adam's sin and were perfectly able to fulfill the law without divine aid. Pelagius denied Augustine's theory of [[original sin]]. Adherents of Pelagius cited [[Book of Deuteronomy|Deuteronomy]] 24:16 in support of their position. Pelagius was declared a [[heresy|heretic]] by the [[Council of Ephesus]] in 431. His interpretation of a doctrine of free will became known as [[Pelagianism]].\n\nHe was well educated, fluent in both [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]], and learned in [[theology]]. He spent time as an ascetic, focusing on practical asceticism. He was well known in Rome, both for the harsh asceticism of his public life and the power and persuasiveness of his speech. His reputation earned him praise early in his career even from such pillars of the Church as Augustine, who referred to him as a \"saintly man.\" However, he was later accused of lying about his own teachings to avoid public condemnation. Most of his later life was spent defending his doctrine against Christian theologians who held that Pelagius was spreading novelties in the Faith unknown to the apostolic tradition.\n\nDue to some calling him a heretic, little of his work has come down to the present day except in the quotes of his opponents. However, more recently, some authors have defended Pelagius as a misunderstood \u201corthodox\u201d:\n{{quote|Recent analysis of his thinking suggests that it was, in fact, highly orthodox, following in the tradition established by the early fathers and in keeping with the teaching of the church in both the East and the West. ...From what we are able to piece together from the few sources available ... it seems that the [[Celts|Celtic]] monk held to an orthodox view of the prevenience of God's grace, and did not assert that individuals could achieve salvation purely by their own efforts.<ref>Bradley, Ian (1993) ''The Celtic Way''. London: Darton, Longman and Todd; p. 62</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n== Beginnings ==\nPelagius was born about 354-360. He is said by his contemporaries, such as Augustine of Hippo, [[Prosper of Aquitaine]], [[Marius Mercator]], and [[Orosius|Paul Orosius]], to have been of British origin.<ref name=DNB>{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21784?docPos=1| accessdate=28 October 2012 |doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> [[Jerome]] apparently thought that Pelagius was Irish, suggesting that he was \"stuffed with Irish porridge\" (''Scotorum pultibus praegravatus'').<ref>Daibhi O Croinin, ''Early Medieval Ireland 400-1200'' (2013), p. 206.</ref> He was tall in stature and portly in appearance. Pelagius was also highly educated, spoke and wrote Latin and Greek with great fluency, and was well versed in theology. His name has traditionally been understood as a Graecized form (from ''p\u00e9lagos'', \"sea\") of the Welsh name Morgan (\"sea-born\"), or another Celtic equivalent.<ref>Dods, Marcus (1911). \"Pelagius\". ''The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', vol. 21. Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\nPelagius became better known around 380 when he moved to Rome.<ref name=Fletcher_11>{{cite book |last= Fletcher|first= Richard|title= Who's Who in Roman Britain and Anglo-Saxon England|pages=11\u201312|year= 1989|publisher= Shepheard-Walwyn|isbn=0-85683-089-5}}</ref> There he enjoyed a reputation of austerity; he also corresponded with St. [[Paulinus of Nola]].<ref name=pohle>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11604a.htm Pohle, Joseph. \"Pelagius and Pelagianism.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 18 Jan. 2014]</ref> Pelagius became concerned about the moral laxity of society. He blamed this laxity on the theology of [[divine grace]] preached by Augustine, among others. He began to teach a very strict, rigid moralism, emphasizing a natural, innate human ability to attain salvation.<ref name=Filippo>[http://www.ignatiusinsight.com/features2008/sfilippo_augustinepelag_jan08.asp Filippo, Stephen N. \"St. Augustine and Pelagianism\". ''Ignatius Insight'']</ref>\n\nWhen [[Alaric I|Alaric]] sacked Rome in 410, Pelagius and his follower [[Caelestius]] fled to [[Carthage]], where he continued his work.<ref name=Fletcher_11 /> He was in Jerusalem by 415.\n\n== Opponents ==\n[[File:Saint Augustine of Hippo.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Saint Augustine of Hippo]]]]\n\n=== Augustine of Hippo ===\nPelagianism quickly spread, especially around Carthage. Augustine wrote \"''De peccatorum meritis et remissione'' libri III\" (Three Books on the Merits and Forgiveness of Sins) in 412, and \"''De spiritu et littera''\" (On the Spirit and the Letter) in 414. When in 414 disquieting rumours arrived from Sicily and the so-called \"Definitiones Caelestii\", said to be the work of Caelestius, were sent to him, he at once (414 or 415) published the rejoinder, \"De perfectione justitiae hominis.\" In these, he strongly affirmed the existence of original sin, the need for infant baptism, the impossibility of a sinless life without Christ, and the necessity of Christ's grace. Augustine stands as an important source on the life and theology of Pelagius, and wrote about him extensively.<ref name=pohle/>\n\n=== Jerome ===\nPelagius soon left for Palestine, befriending the bishop there. Jerome, who also lived there, became involved, as well.  Pelagius had criticized his commentary on the Epistle to the Ephesians.<ref name=pohle/> Jerome wrote against Pelagius in his \"''Letter to Ctesiphon''\" and \"''Dialogus contra Pelagianos''\". With Jerome at the time was [[Paulus Orosius|Orosius]], a visiting pupil of Augustine, with similar views on the dangers of Pelagianism. Together, they publicly condemned Pelagius. Bishop [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John of Jerusalem]], a personal friend of Pelagius, called a council in July 415. Church sources claim Orosius' lack of fluency in Greek rendered him unconvincing and John's Eastern background made him more willing to accept that humans did not have inherent sinfulness, yet the council rendered no verdict and passed the controversy to the Latin Church because Pelagius, Jerome, and Orosius were all Latin.\n\n=== Diospolis ===\nA few months later in December of 415, another synod in [[Lod|Diospolis]] (Lydda) under the bishop of C\u00e6sarea was called by two deposed bishops who came to the Holy Land. However, neither bishop attended for unrelated reasons and Orosius had left after consultation with Bishop John. Pelagius explained to the synod that he did believe God was necessary for salvation because every human is created by God. He also claimed that many works of [[Celestius]] did not represent his own views. He showed letters of recommendation by other authoritative figures including Augustine himself, who for all their disagreements, thought highly of Pelagius' character.\n\nThe [[Synod of Diospolis]] therefore concluded: \"Now since we have received satisfaction in respect of the charges brought against the monk Pelagius in his presence and since he gives his assent to sound doctrines but condemns and anathematises those contrary to the faith of the Church, we adjudge him to belong to the communion of the Catholic Church.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Synod_Lydda_415AD.html|title=Pie_Pelagius_Synod_Lydda_415AD|website=www.seanmultimedia.com|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Pelagius and the doctrine of free will ==\nAfter his acquittal in Diospolis, Pelagius wrote two major treatises which are no longer extant, ''On Nature'' and ''Defense of the Freedom of the Will''. In these, he defends his position on sin and sinlessness, and accuses Augustine of being under the influence of [[Manichaeism]] by elevating evil to the same status as God and teaching pagan fatalism as if it were a Christian doctrine.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nManichaeism stressed that the spirit was God-created, while material substance was corrupt and evil. Theologian Gerald Bonner felt that part of Pelagius' analysis was an over-reaction to Manicheanism. Pelagius held that everything created by God was good, therefore, he could not see how God had made humans fallen creatures.<ref>Bonner, Gerald. ''St. Augustine of Hippo: Life and Controversies'', Philadelphia: The Westminister Press, 1963</ref> (Augustine's teachings on the Fall of Adam was not a settled doctrine at the time the Augustinian/Pelagian dispute began.)\n\nThe view that mankind can avoid sinning, and that humans can freely choose to obey God's commandments, stands at the core of Pelagian teaching. Pelagius stressed human autonomy and freedom of the will.<ref name=Filippo/>\n\nAn illustration of Pelagius' views on man's \"moral ability\" not to sin can be found in his \"Letter to Demetrias\".<ref>[http://silouanthompson.net/library/early-church/pelagius-to-demetrias \"Letter of Pelagius to Demetrias\", ''The Letters of Pelagius'' (Robert Van de Weyer, ed.)]</ref> He was in the Holy Land when, in 413, he received a letter from the renowned [[Anicia (gens)|Anician]] family in Rome. One of the aristocratic ladies who had been among his followers, Anicia Juliana, was writing to a number of eminent Western theologians, including Jerome and possibly Augustine, for moral advice for her 14-year-old daughter, [[Demetrias (daughter of Anicius Hermogenianus Olybrius)|Demetrias]].  Pelagius used the letter to argue his case for morality, stressing his views of natural sanctity and man's moral capacity to choose to live a holy life.  It is perhaps the only extant writing in Pelagius' own hand, and it was thought to be a letter by Jerome for centuries, though Augustine himself references it in his work, ''On the Grace of Christ''.\n\n==Pelagius on grace==\n[[File:Pelagius.jpg|thumb|A 17th-century [[Calvinist]] print depicting Pelagius: The caption says:<br />\"Accurst Pelagius, with what false pretence<br />Durst thou excuse Man's foul Concupiscence,<br />Or cry down Sin Originall, or that<br /> The Love of GOD did Man predestinate.\"]]\nFor Pelagius, \"grace\" consisted of the gift of free will, the Law of Moses, and the teachings of Jesus.<ref>Stephen J. Duffy, Stephen J., ''The Dynamics of Grace: Perspectives in Theological Anthropology'', Collegeville, Minnesota: The Liturgical Press, 1993</ref> With these, a person would be able to perceive the moral course of action and follow it. Prayer, fasting, and asceticism supported the will to do good. Augustine accused Pelagius of thinking of God's grace as consisting only of external helps.\n\nExtant letters of Pelagius and his followers claim that all good works are done only with the grace of God (which he saw as enabling, but not forcing, good works), that infants must be baptized for salvation, and that the saints were not always sinless, but that some at least have been able to stop sinning.\n\nHe instead said, \"This grace we for our part do not, as you suppose, allow to consist merely in the law, but also in the help of God. God helps us by His teaching and revelation, whilst He opens the eyes of our heart; whilst He points out to us the future, that we may not be absorbed in the present; whilst He discovers to us the snares of the devil; whilst He enlightens us with the manifold and ineffable gift of heavenly grace.\" In a letter to the Pope defending himself, he stated, \"This free will is in all good works always assisted by divine help\", and in an accompanying confession of faith, \"Free-will we do so own, as to say that we always stand in need of God's help\", However, he affirmed that \"We do also abhor the blasphemy of those who say that any impossible thing is commanded to man by God; or that the commandments of God cannot be performed by any one man\" (a statement which the pope approved of upon receiving the letter), whereas Augustine famously stated \"''non possum non peccare''\" (\"I cannot not sin\").\n\n==Pope Innocent I ==\nIn the fall of 416, Augustine and four other bishops wrote a letter urging [[Pope Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism.  Innocent I responded by rejecting the Pelagian teachings and excluding Pelagius and Celestius from communion with the Catholic Church until they should recant. Shortly after this, Innocent I died in March of 417.\n\n==Pope Zosimus ==\nSeeking to undo his condemnation, Pelagius wrote a letter and statement of belief to [[Pope Zosimus]], Innocent I's successor, showing himself to be orthodox. In these he articulated his beliefs so as not to contradict what the synods condemned.  Zosimus was persuaded by Celestius to reopen the case, but opposition from the African bishops and [[Honorius (emperor)|Emperor Honorius]] forced Zosimus to condemn and excommunicate Celestius and Pelagius in 418.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nPelagianism was condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)|Council of Carthage in 418]].<ref name=Filippo/>  Augustine, shocked that Pelagius and Celestius were not denounced as heretics, called the Council of Carthage in 418 and stated nine beliefs of the Church that Pelagianism denied:\n\n# Death came from sin, not man's physical nature.\n# Infants must be baptized to be cleansed from original sin.\n# Justifying grace covers past sins and helps avoid future sins.\n# The grace of Christ imparts strength and will to act out God's commandments.\n# No good works can come without God's grace.\n# We confess we are sinners because it is true, not from humility.\n# The saints ask for forgiveness for their own sins.\n# The saints also confess to be sinners because they are.\n# Children dying without baptism are excluded from both the kingdom of heaven and eternal life.\n\n== Death and later ==\nAfter his condemnation, Pelagius was expelled from Jerusalem, and Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]] allowed him to settle in Egypt. He is not heard of thereafter.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nHis death did not end his teachings, although those who followed him may have modified those teachings.  Because little information remains with regard to Pelagius' actual teachings, some of his doctrines possibly were subject to revision and suppression by his enemies (followers of Augustine and the Church leadership as a whole at that time).\n\nPelagius and Caelestius were declared heretics by the [[First Council of Ephesus]] in 431.<ref>Schaff, Philip. [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214.x.xvi.vii.html The Seven Ecumenical Councils: Excursus on Pelagianism], ''Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers'', series II, vol 14.</ref>\n\nBelief in Pelagianism and [[Semipelagianism]] was common for the next few centuries, especially in Britain, the Holy Land, and North Africa. [[Germanus of Auxerre|St Germanus]] visited Britain to combat Pelagianism in or around AD 429. In Wales, [[Saint David]] was credited with convening the [[Synod of Brefi]] and the [[Synod of Victory]] against the followers of Pelagius in the sixth century.\n\n==Evaluation==\nAn objective view of Pelagius and his effect is difficult. His name has been used as an epithet for centuries by both Protestants and Catholics, and he has had few defenders. The very early church denounced his ideas and the Reformation accused Roman Catholics of adhering to his beliefs and condemned both Pelagius and the Catholic Church. Modern scholarship suggests that Pelagius did not take the more extreme positions later associated with his followers.<ref name=Clark>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111006045016/http://americanphilosophy.net/pelagianheresy.htm Clark, R. Scott. \"Pelagianism\", Wheaton College, spring 1997]</ref> [[Ronald Hutton]] describes him as \"a first-rate theologian\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pagan Britain|first=Ronald|last=Hutton|authorlink=Ronald Hutton|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, US|year=2013|isbn=978-0-300-19771-6|page=280}}</ref>\n\n==Pelagius in literature and film==\nIn [[Hilaire Belloc]]'s ''The Four Men'', the Sailor leads his companions in the \"Song of the Pelagian Heresy for the Strengthening of Men's Backs and the very Robust Out-thrusting of Doubtful Doctrine and the Uncertain Intellectual\".\n\nPaul Morgan's novella, ''The Pelagius Book'' (2005), deals with the relationship of Pelagius, and Celestius, who in the story, is sent to spread Pelagius' teachings in Britain.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/Reviews/The-Pelagius-Book/2005/06/10/1118347580857.html &nbsp; Pierce, Peter. Review of ''The Pelagius Book'', \"The Age\", June 11, 2005. Melbourne: Fairfax Digital]</ref>\n\nIn [[M J Trow]] and Richard Denham's 'Britannia' series, Pelagius is a character who has a huge moral impact on one of the four central characters, Vitalis, and his take on Christianity resonates throughout the rest of the series.\n\nPelagius is referred to in [[Stephen Lawhead]]'s book, ''The Black Rood''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=The black rood |date=2000 |publisher=EOS |location=New York |isbn=9780061050343 |url=https://archive.org/details/blackrood00lawh |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=English |url-access=registration }}</ref>, and makes an appearance in ''Patrick''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=Patrick : Son of Ireland |date=2004 |publisher=HarperTorch |location=New York |isbn=9780060012823 |url=https://archive.org/details/patrick00step |accessdate=19 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>, where he has a discussion with the Hiberno-British saint.\n\nPelagius is frequently referred to in [[Jack Whyte]]'s series of books known as ''[[A Dream of Eagles]]'', where a major character's belief in Pelagius' ideas of free will and the laxity of the [[Roman Catholic]] Church eventually cause him to come into conflict with Church representatives.\n\n[[John Cowper Powys]]' novel ''[[Porius (A Romance of the Dark Ages)]]'' (1951) features the conflict between Augustinian/Pelagian beliefs, with the eponymous hero being a follower of Pelagius. Powys referred approvingly to Pelagianism in his nonfiction book ''Obstinate Cymric'' (1947).\n\nThe Saint Augustine/Pelagius debate is mockingly discussed in the novel by [[Flann O'Brien]] titled ''[[The Dalkey Archive]]'', wherein Saint Augustine actually makes a ghostly appearance.\n\nThe government of the English-speaking Union (Enspun) in [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[The Wanting Seed]]'' is locked in a perpetual cycle, rotating between the 'Pel-Phase', named after Pelagius, and an Augustinian phase. The former is one of police and social services; the latter is characterized by martial law. Burgess took up the Augustine/Pelagius theme again in ''[[The Clockwork Testament, or Enderby's End|The Clockwork Testament]]'' and in ''[[Earthly Powers]]''.\n\nIn the movie ''[[King Arthur (2004 film)|King Arthur]]'' (2004),<ref>[http://www.script-o-rama.com/movie_scripts/k/king-arthur-script-transcript.html \"King Arthur\"]</ref> Pelagius is a former mentor of young Lucius Artorius Castus ([[King Arthur|Arthur]]) played by Clive Owen. Arthur champions Pelagius' ideals, particularly those regarding free will. Upon learning of Pelagius's excommunication and death, Arthur realizes that the Roman ideal that he supported no longer exists.  He breaks ties with the [[Roman Empire]], and leads the [[Britons (historic)|Britons]] against the [[Saxon people|Saxon]] invaders.\n\nPelagius is the subject of a poem by the [[Glasgow]] poet [[Edwin Morgan (poet)|Edwin Morgan]] (\"Cathures\", Carcanet 2002) which imagines that Pelagius has returned to his native Glasgow (Cathures) and that his Celtic name was Morgan.\n\n[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]], in his novel ''[[Emperor (Baxter novel)|Emperor]]'', imagines how time's tapestry would have looked had Pelagius' views and not Augustine's influenced the evolution of Christianity.  He also portrays the Emperor Constantine's actions as having dealt a harsh blow, but not necessarily a mortal one, to Pelagius' teaching that humans are free and sin is not inherent in us.\n\nA facsimile of the 1808 \"A Dissertation of the Pelagian Heresy and the Refutation of it al Llandewi Brevi by St David\" has been printed in [[Carmarthen]] on the same street as the original.\n\n''Heresy: the Life of Pelagius'' (2012) by David Lovejoy, portrays Pelagius through the eyes of his (fictional) servant Arwel.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=794693050&qt=results_page Heresy: the Life of Pelagius by David Lovejoy, Echo Publications]</ref>\n\nIn his [[Sister Fidelma mysteries|Sister Fidelma mystery series]] (1994\u2013present), author Peter Berresford Ellis, under the pen name Peter Tremayne, uses the teachings of Pelagius to contrast the dogma and practices of the contemporary Celtic church and that of Rome for supremacy in the British Isles.\n\n== Writings==\nPelagius wrote: ''De fide Trinitatis libri \u2162'' (\"On Faith in the Trinity: Three Books\"), ''Eclogarum ex divinis Scripturis liber primus'' (\"Excerpts out of Divine Scriptures: Book One\"), and ''Commentarii in epistolas S. Pauli'' (\"Commentary on the Epistles of Saint Paul\").  Unfortunately, most of his work survives only in the quotations of his opponents. Only in the past century have works attributable to Pelagius been identified as such.\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Letters.html Letters of Pelagius: To a Presbyter, Augustine of Hippo, and Pope Innocent I]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_On_Nature.html On Nature]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Defense_Of_The_Freedom_Of_The_Will.html Defense of the Freedom of the Will]\n* ''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans''<ref>''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans'' (translated with introduction and notes by Theodore de Bruyn), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1993 {{ISBN|0-19-814399-0}}</ref>\n*''Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul''<ref>\"Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul\"  ''(edited by A. Souter) Texts and Studies; 9, 3 vols. in 1. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1922\u20131931 1: Introduction'' 2: Text \u2013 3: Pseudo-Jerome interpolations</ref>\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Chapters.html Excerpts Out of Divine Scriptures: One Book (a.k.a. Chapters)]\n*[http://seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Confession_Of_Faith.html Confession of Faith]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Written_Anathema.html Written Anathema]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Julian of Eclanum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brinley Rees, ''Pelagius A Reluctant Heretic'', The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1988.\n* Brinley Rees (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0851157149 ''Pelagius: Life and Letters''],  The Boydell Press, Woodbridge:1989, 1991. {{ISBN|0-85115-282-1}} Translation of 18 letters, including ''Epistle to Demetrias'', and minor treatises attributed at various times to Pelagius or his followers.{{ISBN|0-85115-714-9}} \n* Robert Van de Weyer (ed.), ''The Letters of Pelagius: Celtic Soul Friend'', Little Gidding books, Evesham: Arthur James, 1995.\n* Pelagius, ''Epistula ad Demetriadem. Brief an Demetrias'', Einleitung, Edition und \u00dcbersetzung von Gisbert Greshake, [Fontes Christiani], Band 65, Herder, Freiburg, 2015\n* Squires, Stuart. The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls.  Eugene: Wipf and Stock, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{wikisource author-inline}}\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Council_Of_Carthage_May_1_418.html Canons From The Council Of Carthage Against Pelagianism, May 1, 418]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140317175252/http://www.brojed.org/pelagius.html &nbsp; Deacon Geoffrey \u00d3 Riada. ''Pelagius: To Demetrias''. An analysis of the letter and a brief biography.{{dead link|date=October 2014}}]\n*[http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/main/pelagius/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.shtml Latin] and [http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/public/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.htm English] versions of a short section of the letter to Demetrias.\n* {{In Our Time|The Pelagian Controversy|b010dstl|}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:418 deaths]]\n[[Category:4th-century births]]\n[[Category:5th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:5th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:5th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Ascetics]]\n[[Category:Founders of religions]]\n[[Category:Latin letter writers]]\n[[Category:People declared heretics by the first seven ecumenical councils]]\n[[Category:Romano-British Christians]]\n", "text_old": "{{other uses}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{Undue weight|date=June 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n}}\n[[File:Pelagius from Nuremberg Chronicle.jpg|thumb|Illustration of Pelagius in the [[Nuremberg Chronicle]]]]\n\n'''Pelagius'''  ({{circa|AD&nbsp;354}}&nbsp;\u2013 418) was a [[theologian]] who advocated [[free will]] and [[asceticism]]. He was accused by [[Augustine of Hippo]] and others of denying the need for divine aid in performing [[good works]]. They understood him to have said that the only grace necessary was the declaration of the law; humans were not wounded by Adam's sin and were perfectly able to fulfill the law without divine aid. Pelagius denied Augustine's theory of [[original sin]]. Adherents of Pelagius cited [[Book of Deuteronomy|Deuteronomy]] 24:16 in support of their position. Pelagius was declared a [[heresy|heretic]] by the [[Council of Ephesus]] in 431. His interpretation of a doctrine of free will became known as [[Pelagianism]].\n\nHe was well educated, fluent in both [[Ancient Greek|Greek]] and [[Latin]], and learned in [[theology]]. He spent time as an ascetic, focusing on practical asceticism. He was well known in Rome, both for the harsh asceticism of his public life and the power and persuasiveness of his speech. His reputation earned him praise early in his career even from such pillars of the Church as Augustine, who referred to him as a \"saintly man.\" However, he was later accused of lying about his own teachings to avoid public condemnation. Most of his later life was spent defending his doctrine against Christian theologians who held that Pelagius was spreading novelties in the Faith unknown to the apostolic tradition.\n\nDue to some calling him a heretic, little of his work has come down to the present day except in the quotes of his opponents. However, more recently, some authors have defended Pelagius as a misunderstood \u201corthodox\u201d:\n{{quote|Recent analysis of his thinking suggests that it was, in fact, highly orthodox, following in the tradition established by the early fathers and in keeping with the teaching of the church in both the East and the West. ...From what we are able to piece together from the few sources available ... it seems that the [[Celts|Celtic]] monk held to an orthodox view of the prevenience of God's grace, and did not assert that individuals could achieve salvation purely by their own efforts.<ref>Bradley, Ian (1993) ''The Celtic Way''. London: Darton, Longman and Todd; p. 62</ref>|author=|title=|source=}}\n\n== Beginnings ==\nPelagius was born about 354-360. He is said by his contemporaries, such as Augustine of Hippo, [[Prosper of Aquitaine]], [[Marius Mercator]], and [[Orosius|Paul Orosius]], to have been of British origin.<ref name=DNB>{{cite encyclopedia |first=Gerald |last = Bonner|authorlink=| publisher = Oxford University Press | encyclopedia= Oxford Dictionary of National Biography| title= Pelagius (fl. c.390\u2013418), theologian| year = 2004 | url = http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/21784?docPos=1| accessdate=28 October 2012 |doi= 10.1093/ref:odnb/21784 }} {{ODNBsub}}</ref> [[Jerome]] apparently thought that Pelagius was Irish, suggesting that he was \"stuffed with Irish porridge\" (''Scotorum pultibus praegravatus'').<ref>Daibhi O Croinin, ''Early Medieval Ireland 400-1200'' (2013), p. 206.</ref> He was tall in stature and portly in appearance. Pelagius was also highly educated, spoke and wrote Latin and Greek with great fluency, and was well versed in theology. His name has traditionally been understood as a Graecized form (from ''p\u00e9lagos'', \"sea\") of the Welsh name Morgan (\"sea-born\"), or another Celtic equivalent.<ref>Dods, Marcus (1911). \"Pelagius\". ''The Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'', vol. 21. Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\nPelagius became better known around 380 when he moved to Rome.<ref name=Fletcher_11>{{cite book |last= Fletcher|first= Richard|title= Who's Who in Roman Britain and Anglo-Saxon England|pages=11\u201312|year= 1989|publisher= Shepheard-Walwyn|isbn=0-85683-089-5}}</ref> There he enjoyed a reputation of austerity; he also corresponded with St. [[Paulinus of Nola]].<ref name=pohle>[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11604a.htm Pohle, Joseph. \"Pelagius and Pelagianism.\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 18 Jan. 2014]</ref> Pelagius became concerned about the moral laxity of society. He blamed this laxity on the theology of [[divine grace]] preached by Augustine, among others. He began to teach a very strict, rigid moralism, emphasizing a natural, innate human ability to attain salvation.<ref name=Filippo>[http://www.ignatiusinsight.com/features2008/sfilippo_augustinepelag_jan08.asp Filippo, Stephen N. \"St. Augustine and Pelagianism\". ''Ignatius Insight'']</ref>\n\nWhen [[Alaric I|Alaric]] sacked Rome in 410, Pelagius and his follower [[Caelestius]] fled to [[Carthage]], where he continued his work.<ref name=Fletcher_11 /> He was in Jerusalem by 415.\n\n== Opponents ==\n[[File:Saint Augustine of Hippo.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Saint Augustine of Hippo]]]]\n\n=== Augustine of Hippo ===\nPelagianism quickly spread, especially around Carthage. Augustine wrote \"''De peccatorum meritis et remissione'' libri III\" (Three Books on the Merits and Forgiveness of Sins) in 412, and \"''De spiritu et littera''\" (On the Spirit and the Letter) in 414. When in 414 disquieting rumours arrived from Sicily and the so-called \"Definitiones Caelestii\", said to be the work of Caelestius, were sent to him, he at once (414 or 415) published the rejoinder, \"De perfectione justitiae hominis.\" In these, he strongly affirmed the existence of original sin, the need for infant baptism, the impossibility of a sinless life without Christ, and the necessity of Christ's grace. Augustine stands as an important source on the life and theology of Pelagius, and wrote about him extensively.<ref name=pohle/>\n\n=== Jerome ===\nPelagius soon left for Palestine, befriending the bishop there. Jerome, who also lived there, became involved, as well.  Pelagius had criticized his commentary on the Epistle to the Ephesians.<ref name=pohle/> Jerome wrote against Pelagius in his \"''Letter to Ctesiphon''\" and \"''Dialogus contra Pelagianos''.\" With Jerome at the time was [[Paulus Orosius|Orosius]], a visiting pupil of Augustine, with similar views on the dangers of Pelagianism. Together, they publicly condemned Pelagius. Bishop [[John II, Bishop of Jerusalem|John of Jerusalem]], a personal friend of Pelagius, called a council in July 415. Church sources claim Orosius' lack of fluency in Greek rendered him unconvincing and John's Eastern background made him more willing to accept that humans did not have inherent sinfulness, yet the council rendered no verdict and passed the controversy to the Latin Church because Pelagius, Jerome, and Orosius were all Latin.\n\n=== Diospolis ===\nA few months later in December of 415, another synod in [[Lod|Diospolis]] (Lydda) under the bishop of C\u00e6sarea was called by two deposed bishops who came to the Holy Land. However, neither bishop attended for unrelated reasons and Orosius had left after consultation with Bishop John. Pelagius explained to the synod that he did believe God was necessary for salvation because every human is created by God. He also claimed that many works of [[Celestius]] did not represent his own views. He showed letters of recommendation by other authoritative figures including Augustine himself, who for all their disagreements, thought highly of Pelagius' character.\n\nThe [[Synod of Diospolis]] therefore concluded: \"Now since we have received satisfaction in respect of the charges brought against the monk Pelagius in his presence and since he gives his assent to sound doctrines but condemns and anathematises those contrary to the faith of the Church, we adjudge him to belong to the communion of the Catholic Church.\"<ref>[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Synod_Lydda_415AD.html Jennings, Daniel R., \"Pelagius: Transcript From The Council of Diospolis (Lydda) Against Pelagius, 415AD]</ref>\n\n== Pelagius and the doctrine of free will ==\nAfter his acquittal in Diospolis, Pelagius wrote two major treatises which are no longer extant, ''On Nature'' and ''Defense of the Freedom of the Will''. In these, he defends his position on sin and sinlessness, and accuses Augustine of being under the influence of [[Manichaeism]] by elevating evil to the same status as God and teaching pagan fatalism as if it were a Christian doctrine.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}}\n\nManichaeism stressed that the spirit was God-created, while material substance was corrupt and evil. Theologian Gerald Bonner felt that part of Pelagius' analysis was an over-reaction to Manicheanism. Pelagius held that everything created by God was good, therefore, he could not see how God had made humans fallen creatures.<ref>Bonner, Gerald. ''St. Augustine of Hippo: Life and Controversies'', Philadelphia: The Westminister Press, 1963</ref> (Augustine's teachings on the Fall of Adam was not a settled doctrine at the time the Augustinian/Pelagian dispute began.)\n\nThe view that mankind can avoid sinning, and that humans can freely choose to obey God's commandments, stands at the core of Pelagian teaching. Pelagius stressed human autonomy and freedom of the will.<ref name=Filippo/>\n\nAn illustration of Pelagius' views on man's \"moral ability\" not to sin can be found in his \"Letter to Demetrias\".<ref>[http://silouanthompson.net/library/early-church/pelagius-to-demetrias \"Letter of Pelagius to Demetrias\", ''The Letters of Pelagius'' (Robert Van de Weyer, ed.)]</ref> He was in the Holy Land when, in 413, he received a letter from the renowned [[Anicia (gens)|Anician]] family in Rome. One of the aristocratic ladies who had been among his followers, Anicia Juliana, was writing to a number of eminent Western theologians, including Jerome and possibly Augustine, for moral advice for her 14-year-old daughter, [[Demetrias (daughter of Anicius Hermogenianus Olybrius)|Demetrias]].  Pelagius used the letter to argue his case for morality, stressing his views of natural sanctity and man's moral capacity to choose to live a holy life.  It is perhaps the only extant writing in Pelagius' own hand, and it was thought to be a letter by Jerome for centuries, though Augustine himself references it in his work, ''On the Grace of Christ''.\n\n==Pelagius on grace==\n[[File:Pelagius.jpg|thumb|A 17th-century [[Calvinist]] print depicting Pelagius: The caption says:<br />\"Accurst Pelagius, with what false pretence<br />Durst thou excuse Man's foul Concupiscence,<br />Or cry down Sin Originall, or that<br /> The Love of GOD did Man predestinate.\"]]\nFor Pelagius, \"grace\" consisted of the gift of free will, the Law of Moses, and the teachings of Jesus.<ref>Stephen J. Duffy, Stephen J., ''The Dynamics of Grace: Perspectives in Theological Anthropology'', Collegeville, Minnesota: The Liturgical Press, 1993</ref> With these, a person would be able to perceive the moral course of action and follow it. Prayer, fasting, and asceticism supported the will to do good. Augustine accused Pelagius of thinking of God's grace as consisting only of external helps.\n\nExtant letters of Pelagius and his followers claim that all good works are done only with the grace of God (which he saw as enabling, but not forcing, good works), that infants must be baptized for salvation, and that the saints were not always sinless, but that some at least have been able to stop sinning.\n\nHe instead said, \"This grace we for our part do not, as you suppose, allow to consist merely in the law, but also in the help of God. God helps us by His teaching and revelation, whilst He opens the eyes of our heart; whilst He points out to us the future, that we may not be absorbed in the present; whilst He discovers to us the snares of the devil; whilst He enlightens us with the manifold and ineffable gift of heavenly grace.\" In a letter to the Pope defending himself, he stated, \"This free will is in all good works always assisted by divine help\", and in an accompanying confession of faith, \"Free-will we do so own, as to say that we always stand in need of God's help\", However, he affirmed that \"We do also abhor the blasphemy of those who say that any impossible thing is commanded to man by God; or that the commandments of God cannot be performed by any one man\" (a statement which the pope approved of upon receiving the letter), whereas Augustine famously stated \"''non possum non peccare''\" (\"I cannot not sin\").\n\n==Pope Innocent I ==\nIn the fall of 416, Augustine and four other bishops wrote a letter urging [[Pope Innocent I]] to condemn Pelagianism.  Innocent I responded by rejecting the Pelagian teachings and excluding Pelagius and Celestius from communion with the Catholic Church until they should recant. Shortly after this, Innocent I died in March of 417.\n\n==Pope Zosimus ==\nSeeking to undo his condemnation, Pelagius wrote a letter and statement of belief to [[Pope Zosimus]], Innocent I's successor, showing himself to be orthodox. In these he articulated his beliefs so as not to contradict what the synods condemned.  Zosimus was persuaded by Celestius to reopen the case, but opposition from the African bishops and [[Honorius (emperor)|Emperor Honorius]] forced Zosimus to condemn and excommunicate Celestius and Pelagius in 418.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nPelagianism was condemned at the [[Council of Carthage (418)|Council of Carthage in 418]].<ref name=Filippo/>  Augustine, shocked that Pelagius and Celestius were not denounced as heretics, called the Council of Carthage in 418 and stated nine beliefs of the Church that Pelagianism denied:\n\n# Death came from sin, not man's physical nature.\n# Infants must be baptized to be cleansed from original sin.\n# Justifying grace covers past sins and helps avoid future sins.\n# The grace of Christ imparts strength and will to act out God's commandments.\n# No good works can come without God's grace.\n# We confess we are sinners because it is true, not from humility.\n# The saints ask for forgiveness for their own sins.\n# The saints also confess to be sinners because they are.\n# Children dying without baptism are excluded from both the kingdom of heaven and eternal life.\n\n== Death and later ==\nAfter his condemnation, Pelagius was expelled from Jerusalem, and Saint [[Cyril of Alexandria]] allowed him to settle in Egypt. He is not heard of thereafter.<ref name=DNB/>\n\nHis death did not end his teachings, although those who followed him may have modified those teachings.  Because little information remains with regard to Pelagius' actual teachings, some of his doctrines possibly were subject to revision and suppression by his enemies (followers of Augustine and the Church leadership as a whole at that time).\n\nPelagius and Caelestius were declared heretics by the [[First Council of Ephesus]] in 431.<ref>Schaff, Philip. [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf214.x.xvi.vii.html The Seven Ecumenical Councils: Excursus on Pelagianism], ''Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers'', series II, vol 14.</ref>\n\nBelief in Pelagianism and [[Semipelagianism]] was common for the next few centuries, especially in Britain, the Holy Land, and North Africa. [[Germanus of Auxerre|St Germanus]] visited Britain to combat Pelagianism in or around AD 429. In Wales, [[Saint David]] was credited with convening the [[Synod of Brefi]] and the [[Synod of Victory]] against the followers of Pelagius in the sixth century.\n\n==Evaluation==\nAn objective view of Pelagius and his effect is difficult. His name has been used as an epithet for centuries by both Protestants and Catholics, and he has had few defenders. The very early church denounced his ideas and the Reformation accused Roman Catholics of adhering to his beliefs and condemned both Pelagius and the Catholic Church. Modern scholarship suggests that Pelagius did not take the more extreme positions later associated with his followers.<ref name=Clark>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111006045016/http://americanphilosophy.net/pelagianheresy.htm Clark, R. Scott. \"Pelagianism\", Wheaton College, spring 1997]</ref> [[Ronald Hutton]] describes him as \"a first-rate theologian\".<ref>{{cite book|title=Pagan Britain|first=Ronald|last=Hutton|authorlink=Ronald Hutton|publisher=Yale University Press|location=New Haven, US|year=2013|isbn=978-0-300-19771-6|page=280}}</ref>\n\n==Pelagius in literature and film==\nIn [[Hilaire Belloc]]'s ''The Four Men'', the Sailor leads his companions in the \"Song of the Pelagian Heresy for the Strengthening of Men's Backs and the very Robust Out-thrusting of Doubtful Doctrine and the Uncertain Intellectual\".\n\nPaul Morgan's novella, ''The Pelagius Book'' (2005), deals with the relationship of Pelagius, and Celestius, who in the story, is sent to spread Pelagius' teachings in Britain.<ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/news/Reviews/The-Pelagius-Book/2005/06/10/1118347580857.html &nbsp; Pierce, Peter. Review of ''The Pelagius Book'', \"The Age\", June 11, 2005. Melbourne: Fairfax Digital]</ref>\n\nIn [[M J Trow]] and Richard Denham's 'Britannia' series, Pelagius is a character who has a huge moral impact on one of the four central characters, Vitalis, and his take on Christianity resonates throughout the rest of the series.\n\nPelagius is referred to in [[Stephen Lawhead]]'s book, ''The Black Rood''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=The black rood |date=2000 |publisher=EOS |location=New York |isbn=9780061050343 |url=https://archive.org/details/blackrood00lawh |accessdate=19 January 2019 |language=English |url-access=registration }}</ref>, and makes an appearance in ''Patrick''<ref>{{cite book |last1=Lawhead |first1=Stephen R |title=Patrick : Son of Ireland |date=2004 |publisher=HarperTorch |location=New York |isbn=9780060012823 |url=https://archive.org/details/patrick00step |accessdate=19 January 2019 |url-access=registration }}</ref>, where he has a discussion with the Hiberno-British saint.\n\nPelagius is frequently referred to in [[Jack Whyte]]'s series of books known as ''[[A Dream of Eagles]]'', where a major character's belief in Pelagius' ideas of free will and the laxity of the [[Roman Catholic]] Church eventually cause him to come into conflict with Church representatives.\n\n[[John Cowper Powys]]' novel ''[[Porius (A Romance of the Dark Ages)]]'' (1951) features the conflict between Augustinian/Pelagian beliefs, with the eponymous hero being a follower of Pelagius. Powys referred approvingly to Pelagianism in his nonfiction book ''Obstinate Cymric'' (1947).\n\nThe Saint Augustine/Pelagius debate is mockingly discussed in the novel by [[Flann O'Brien]] titled ''[[The Dalkey Archive]]'', wherein Saint Augustine actually makes a ghostly appearance.\n\nThe government of the English-speaking Union (Enspun) in [[Anthony Burgess]]' ''[[The Wanting Seed]]'' is locked in a perpetual cycle, rotating between the 'Pel-Phase', named after Pelagius, and an Augustinian phase. The former is one of police and social services; the latter is characterized by martial law. Burgess took up the Augustine/Pelagius theme again in ''[[The Clockwork Testament, or Enderby's End|The Clockwork Testament]]'' and in ''[[Earthly Powers]]''.\n\nIn the movie ''[[King Arthur (2004 film)|King Arthur]]'' (2004),<ref>[http://www.script-o-rama.com/movie_scripts/k/king-arthur-script-transcript.html \"King Arthur\"]</ref> Pelagius is a former mentor of young Lucius Artorius Castus ([[King Arthur|Arthur]]) played by Clive Owen. Arthur champions Pelagius' ideals, particularly those regarding free will. Upon learning of Pelagius's excommunication and death, Arthur realizes that the Roman ideal that he supported no longer exists.  He breaks ties with the [[Roman Empire]], and leads the [[Britons (historic)|Britons]] against the [[Saxon people|Saxon]] invaders.\n\nPelagius is the subject of a poem by the [[Glasgow]] poet [[Edwin Morgan (poet)|Edwin Morgan]] (\"Cathures\", Carcanet 2002) which imagines that Pelagius has returned to his native Glasgow (Cathures) and that his Celtic name was Morgan.\n\n[[Stephen Baxter (author)|Stephen Baxter]], in his novel ''[[Emperor (Baxter novel)|Emperor]]'', imagines how time's tapestry would have looked had Pelagius' views and not Augustine's influenced the evolution of Christianity.  He also portrays the Emperor Constantine's actions as having dealt a harsh blow, but not necessarily a mortal one, to Pelagius' teaching that humans are free and sin is not inherent in us.\n\nA facsimile of the 1808 \"A Dissertation of the Pelagian Heresy and the Refutation of it al Llandewi Brevi by St David\" has been printed in [[Carmarthen]] on the same street as the original.\n\n''Heresy: the Life of Pelagius'' (2012) by David Lovejoy, portrays Pelagius through the eyes of his (fictional) servant Arwel.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/search?q=794693050&qt=results_page Heresy: the Life of Pelagius by David Lovejoy, Echo Publications]</ref>\n\nIn his [[Sister Fidelma mysteries|Sister Fidelma mystery series]] (1994\u2013present), author Peter Berresford Ellis, under the pen name Peter Tremayne, uses the teachings of Pelagius to contrast the dogma and practices of the contemporary Celtic church and that of Rome for supremacy in the British Isles.\n\n== Writings==\nPelagius wrote: ''De fide Trinitatis libri \u2162'' (\"On Faith in the Trinity: Three Books\"), ''Eclogarum ex divinis Scripturis liber primus'' (\"Excerpts out of Divine Scriptures: Book One\"), and ''Commentarii in epistolas S. Pauli'' (\"Commentary on the Epistles of Saint Paul\").  Unfortunately, most of his work survives only in the quotations of his opponents. Only in the past century have works attributable to Pelagius been identified as such.\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Letters.html Letters of Pelagius: To a Presbyter, Augustine of Hippo, and Pope Innocent I]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_On_Nature.html On Nature]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Defense_Of_The_Freedom_Of_The_Will.html Defense of the Freedom of the Will]\n* ''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans''<ref>''Pelagius's Commentary on St Paul's Epistle to the Romans'' (translated with introduction and notes by Theodore de Bruyn), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1993 {{ISBN|0-19-814399-0}}</ref>\n*''Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul''<ref>\"Pelagius's Expositions of the Thirteen Epistles of St. Paul\"  ''(edited by A. Souter) Texts and Studies; 9, 3 vols. in 1. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 1922\u20131931 1: Introduction'' 2: Text \u2013 3: Pseudo-Jerome interpolations</ref>\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Chapters.html Excerpts Out of Divine Scriptures: One Book (a.k.a. Chapters)]\n*[http://seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Confession_Of_Faith.html Confession of Faith]\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Pelagius_Written_Anathema.html Written Anathema]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Julian of Eclanum]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Brinley Rees, ''Pelagius A Reluctant Heretic'', The Boydell Press, Woodbridge, 1988.\n* Brinley Rees (ed.), [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0851157149 ''Pelagius: Life and Letters''],  The Boydell Press, Woodbridge:1989, 1991. {{ISBN|0-85115-282-1}} Translation of 18 letters, including ''Epistle to Demetrias'', and minor treatises attributed at various times to Pelagius or his followers.{{ISBN|0-85115-714-9}} \n* Robert Van de Weyer (ed.), ''The Letters of Pelagius: Celtic Soul Friend'', Little Gidding books, Evesham: Arthur James, 1995.\n* Pelagius, ''Epistula ad Demetriadem. Brief an Demetrias'', Einleitung, Edition und \u00dcbersetzung von Gisbert Greshake, [Fontes Christiani], Band 65, Herder, Freiburg, 2015\n* Squires, Stuart. The Pelagian Controversy: An Introduction to the Enemies of Grace and the Conspiracy of Lost Souls.  Eugene: Wipf and Stock, 2019.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Commons category-inline}}\n*{{wikisource author-inline}}\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[http://www.seanmultimedia.com/Pie_Council_Of_Carthage_May_1_418.html Canons From The Council Of Carthage Against Pelagianism, May 1, 418]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20140317175252/http://www.brojed.org/pelagius.html &nbsp; Deacon Geoffrey \u00d3 Riada. ''Pelagius: To Demetrias''. An analysis of the letter and a brief biography.{{dead link|date=October 2014}}]\n*[http://www.earlychurchtexts.com/main/pelagius/pelagius_letter_to_demetrias.s