{"title_page": "Jacob Vita Pardo", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Jacob Pardo}}\n'''Jacob Vita Pardo '''({{Lang-he|\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05d7\u05d9 \u05e4\u05d0\u05e8\u05d3\u05d5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Almanzzi|first=Giuseppe|author-link=Joseph Almanzi|year=1856|editor-last=Blumenfeld|editor-first=Ignaz|editor-link=|script-title=he:\u05d0\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8 \u05e0\u05d7\u05de\u05d3|trans-title=Ozar Nechmad|url=http://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=21157&st=&pgnum=179|language=he|volume=1|location=[[Wien]]|pages=170, 172|access-date=Sep 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=az>{{cite book|year=1841|script-title=he:\u05d0\u05d1\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05db\u05e8\u05d5\u05df|trans-title=Denksteine|url=http://hebrewbooks.org/37974|language=Hebrew|location=Prague|access-date=Sep 8, 2015}}</ref>) was an [[author]] and [[preacher]]. He was born at [[Ragusa (Croatia)|Ragusa]] in 1822 to David Samuel Pardo, and died in 1843 at [[Padua]], where he studied at the Collegium Rabbinicum under [[Samuel David Luzzatto]]. His body was transported to [[Verona]] for burial. Five of his sermons, preached in Padua and Verona, were published after his death. When but eighteen years old he wrote a [[Bible commentary|commentary]] on [[Book of Micah|Micah]], which was published by Luzzatto as the first supplement to [[Joseph Almanzi]]'s \"''Abne Zikkaron'',\" [[Prague]], 1841. The commentary is not complete, extending only to chapter 4 verse 8. An [[obituary]], written by Luzzatto in memory of his talented pupil, serves as an introduction to the work.<ref name=az/><ref>{{JewishEncyclopedia|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11906-pardo#anchor6|title=Jacob Vita Pardo|author=S. O.|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}<br />'''Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography:'''\n*[[Moritz Steinschneider|Steinschneider]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=HCZSAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:Steinschneider&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBzgUahUKEwjM7qvB5IbIAhWMlQ0KHQ69Dzg#v=onepage&q&f=false Cat. Bodl.]'' cols. 883-884, 1245-1246, 1517-1518;\n*Azulai, ''Shem ha-Gedolim'', p. 46;\n*[[Fuenn]], ''Keneset Yisrael'', i. 48b;\n*[[Marco Mortara|Mortara]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uWs-AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Pardo&f=false Indice]'';\n*[[Benjacob]], ''[http://hebrewbooks.org/50068 O\u1e93ar ha-Sefarim]'', pp. 46, 312 et passim;\n*''O\u1e93ar Ne\u1e25mad'', i. [http://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=21157&st=&pgnum=179&hilite= 170];\n*''[http://hebrewbooks.org/37974 Abne Zikkaron]'', Supplements 2 and 3, Prague, 1841;\n*[[Julius F\u00fcrst|F\u00fcrst]], ''{{abbr|Bibl. Jud.|Bibliotheca Judaica}}'' iii. [https://books.google.com/books?id=YaBNgq3Ze9oC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bibliotheca+Judaica&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCWoVChMIus6cv5WHyAIVCYsNCh2yXwFU#v=onepage&q=seinem%2018.%20Jahre%20geschrieben%2C%20durch%20den%20Tod.&f=false 67].</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pardo, Jacob Vita}}\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1843 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Bible commentators]]\n[[Category:Jewish non-fiction writers]]\n\n\n{{Judaism-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Jacob Pardo}}\n'''Jacob Vita Pardo '''({{Lang-he|\u05d9\u05e2\u05e7\u05d1 \u05d7\u05d9 \u05e4\u05d0\u05e8\u05d3\u05d5}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Almanzzi|first=Giuseppe|author-link=Joseph Almanzi|year=1856|editor-last=Blumenfeld|editor-first=Ignaz|editor-link=|script-title=he:\u05d0\u05d5\u05e6\u05e8 \u05e0\u05d7\u05de\u05d3|trans-title=Ozar Nechmad|url=http://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=21157&st=&pgnum=179|language=he|volume=1|location=[[Wien]]|pages=170, 172|access-date=Sep 20, 2015}}</ref><ref name=az>{{cite book|year=1841|script-title=he:\u05d0\u05d1\u05e0\u05d9 \u05d6\u05db\u05e8\u05d5\u05df|trans-title=Denksteine|url=http://hebrewbooks.org/37974|language=Hebrew|location=Prague|access-date=Sep 8, 2015}}</ref>) was an [[author]] and [[preacher]]. He was born at [[Ragusa (Croatia)|Ragusa]] in 1822 to David Samuel Pardo, and died in 1843 at [[Padua]], where he studied at the Collegium Rabbinicum under [[Samuel David Luzzatto]]. His body was transported to [[Verona]] for burial. Five of his sermons, preached in Padua and Verona, were published after his death. When but eighteen years old he wrote a [[Bible commentary|commentary]] on [[Book of Micah|Micah]], which was published by Luzzatto as the first supplement to [[Joseph Almanzi]]'s \"''Abne Zikkaron'',\" [[Prague]], 1841. The commentary is not complete, extending only to chapter 4 verse 8. An [[obituary]], written by Luzzatto in memory of his talented pupil, serves as an introduction to the work.<ref name=az/><ref>{{JewishEncyclopedia|url=http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/11906-pardo#anchor6|title=Jacob Vita Pardo|author=S. O.|accessdate=August 26, 2015}}<br />'''Jewish Encyclopedia bibliography:'''\n*[[Moritz Steinschneider|Steinschneider]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=HCZSAAAAcAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:Steinschneider&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBzgUahUKEwjM7qvB5IbIAhWMlQ0KHQ69Dzg#v=onepage&q&f=false Cat. Bodl.]'' cols. 883-884, 1245-1246, 1517-1518;\n*Azulai, ''Shem ha-Gedolim'', p. 46;\n*[[Fuenn]], ''Keneset Yisrael'', i. 48b;\n*[[Marco Mortara|Mortara]], ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=uWs-AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=Pardo&f=false Indice]'';\n*[[Benjacob]], ''[http://hebrewbooks.org/50068 O\u1e93ar ha-Sefarim]'', pp. 46, 312 et passim;\n*''O\u1e93ar Ne\u1e25mad'', i. [http://hebrewbooks.org/pdfpager.aspx?req=21157&st=&pgnum=179&hilite= 170];\n*''[http://hebrewbooks.org/37974 Abne Zikkaron]'', Supplements 2 and 3, Prague, 1841;\n*[[Julius F\u00fcrst|F\u00fcrst]], ''{{abbr|Bibl. Jud.|Bibliotheca Judaica}}'' iii. [https://books.google.com/books?id=YaBNgq3Ze9oC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bibliotheca+Judaica&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CF4Q6AEwCWoVChMIus6cv5WHyAIVCYsNCh2yXwFU#v=onepage&q=seinem%2018.%20Jahre%20geschrieben%2C%20durch%20den%20Tod.&f=false 67].</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pardo, Jacob Vita}}\n[[Category:1822 births]]\n[[Category:1843 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:Bible commentators]]\n[[Category:Jewish non-fiction writers]]\n\n{{Judaism-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacob_Vita_Pardo"}
